04/Aug/11 12:05 PM;nfilotto;Here are my remarks :
* The query is incorrect because of setMaxRows that cannot work here mostly due to the fact that we don't have one row per node since we get the properties primaryType, mixinTypes, owner and permissions at the same time for each node. So if your limit is 10, and you have one node with 7 properties and another node with 5, you will get 2 nodes instead of 10 and the second node won't have its 2 last properties which causes an inconsistency issue.

* The value of fromOrderNum must be determinist since we use it as key to store the page content in the cache. The value should be of type 0, 1, 2, 3 (aka the page index) and so on because if you make it depend on the result set if the result set change (due to a delete, move, add...) we could face unpredictable bugs. *So I would even say that we need to replace fromOrderNum with pageIndex.*

* In WorkspaceStorageCache, we need to add a method of type isChildNodesByPageSupported to be able to call getChildNodesData(NodeData) and return false directly when we call CacheableWorkspaceDataManager.getChildNodesDataByPage otherwise for implementation like LinkedWorkspaceStorageCacheImpl that doesn't support this feature the result will never be stored into the cache so it will be very slow.

* In SessionDataManager.getChildNodesDataByPage and TransactionableDataManager.getChildNodesDataByPage, I don't really understand the merge logic: Why the code is different in those two methods ? What about the state isUnchaged() ? Why state.isRenamed() is treated exactly like isAdded() ? In case of isMixinChanged and isUpdated why simply checking if the id exists in the map instead of using the OrderNumber? I mean instead of:
{code}
childs.remove(state.getData());
if (minOrderNum <= data.getOrderNumber() && data.getOrderNumber() <= maxOrderNum)
{
   childs.add(data);
}
{code}
why not simply
{code}
if (childs.remove(state.getData()))
{
   childs.add(data);
}
{code}

